Since we have data from multiple censuses, we can also track change census-over-census, every five years from 2001 in @fig-census-over-census-bar. McKernan/Belgravia trailed the rest of Edmonton in every census period. The station area really only grew in dwellings and population substantially in 2011-2016.


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/fig-census-over-census-bar_61845624a73d1cbe5515b0b78ad1b879'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Census-over-census population and dwelling growth in the McKernan/Belgravia Station area and rest of Edmonton, 2001-2021](index_files/figure-html/fig-census-over-census-bar-1.png){#fig-census-over-census-bar width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-8_0decea05336dc8f9822935ba282f77d0'}

:::


Once again, we can break down the census-over-census change by DB, as shown in @fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-absolute and @fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-percent. We can see the driver of the increase in dwellings in 2011-2016 being the demolition (seen in 2006-2011) and subsequent replacement of the aforementioned low-rise apartments on 76 Ave west of the station. We can also see the second demolition and replacement of low-rise apartments happen across the street in 2016-2021. More recently, we can see the demolition of mostly single-family homes north of the station along University Ave with under construction (at the time) mid-rise apartments that should increase dwellings and population in those blocks in the upcoming census. Most other blocks have largely intensified very gently or remained static.

::: panel-tabset
### Absolute change


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-absolute_a8b13598fa9165ef131bbe945453834a'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Census-over-census absolute change in population and dwellings around McKernan/Belgravia Station](index_files/figure-html/fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-absolute-1.png){#fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-absolute width=672}
:::
:::


### Percent change


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-percent_478b8af371e278a6c62eca22bc571d0c'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Census-over-census percent change in population and dwellings around McKernan/Belgravia Station](index_files/figure-html/fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-percent-1.png){#fig-belmac-census-over-census-change-percent width=672}
:::
:::

:::

To sum up:

-   McKernan/Belgravia Station area has not seen much growth over the past twenty years, especially compared to the rest of Edmonton.

-   The first major driver of growth seems to be demolition and replacement of low-rise apartments with slightly higher density. This means that there was more displacement through demolition than if the surrounding detached homes were replaced with apartments.

-   The second major driver of growth seems to be construction of new mid-rise apartments on the University Ave car sewer. As [others have argued](https://thetyee.ca/Analysis/2021/10/25/Confining-Rental-Homes-To-Busy-Roads-Devil-Bargain/), it is profoundly unequal to confine apartments to busy roads.

## District plans need more transit-oriented development {#sec-no-tod-planned-here}

While the census shows what happened in the past, zoning and district plans together show what we can expect for the future. Data for the new zoning is not yet available, so I pieced it together using the [City's interactive map](https://gis.edmonton.ca/portal/apps/webappviewer/?appalias=CityWideRezoning&id=dd3a43995e7a4e62a46b4c1599a8c8a4) and the equivalences listed in the new zoning bylaw. Data for the nodes and corridors of district planning is also not available so I have drawn these borders manually based on the images in the Scona district plan.


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-11_6584bea35f5f3a29211cb7e54cfd010e'}

:::


@Fig-zoning-district-plan shows the zoning (as of January 1, 2024) and proposed nodes and corridors within the station area. I have also overlaid smaller radii to compare Edmonton's plan with BC's new transit-oriented development legislation that will permit 20 storeys within 200m, 12 storeys within 400m and 8 storeys within the full 800m.

While the vast majority of McKernan/Belgravia station area is RS zoned, this is a slight improvement over the previous bylaw. Looking at the nodes and corridors map, we can see that the secondary corridor only extends at most one block in each direction, except for the University Ave and 114 St intersection. In fact, using the unamended district planning borders, only 31% of the station area will be covered by the nodes and corridors. The rest of the area is planned for low-rise only.


::: {#fig-zoning-district-plan .cell .column-page layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/html/fig-zoning-district-plan_efddafa7ca63dffe6d131e5c42fb3900'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Zoning as of January 1, 2024](index_files/figure-html/fig-zoning-district-plan-1.png){#fig-zoning-district-plan-1 width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Proposed nodes and corridors from district planning](index_files/figure-html/fig-zoning-district-plan-2.png){#fig-zoning-district-plan-2 width=672}
:::

Land use in the McKernan/Belgravia station area
:::

::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-13_fecee91bfc1529a80cafa2dec9b4feb0'}

:::


But, that doesn't tell the whole story, as some plots are zoned for parks, fire halls and other jurisdictions, where housing is unlikely to be built, even through a rezoning. @Fig-nodes-corridors-residential shows the coverage of nodes and corridors when we exclude these zones. The major node to the north at the University of Alberta no longer plays any role in the McKernan/Belgravia Station area. Using this map, only 23% of the station area is covered by the secondary corridors that will support up to 8 storeys.


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/fig-nodes-corridors-residential_b06844680695b737f1b10108bab1f3f9'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Nodes and corridors around McKernan/Belgravia station, only residential zones](index_files/figure-html/fig-nodes-corridors-residential-1.png){#fig-nodes-corridors-residential width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-15_7b2bd261126c4055b658edbf44492511'}

:::

::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-16_9c9d63c0c7c16d288a733ea41a373eca'}

:::


Why stop there? Through DC zoning, local knowledge and some streetview, I identified some sites within the secondary corridor that are either existing, under construction or planned low to mid-rise apartments, shown in @fig-nodes-corridors-planned. I have also excluded the wide 114 St/LRT right-of-way. While arguably one of the older low-rise apartments on the site furthest east along 76 Ave could see an increase in permissions and redevelop, the rest of the sites identified are relatively new and are unlikely to benefit from the secondary corridor permissions. When we remove these sites and the right-of-way, only 15% of the station area remains covered by secondary corridors that will support up to 8 storeys.


::: {#fig-nodes-corridors-planned .cell .column-page layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/html/fig-nodes-corridors-planned_13ac4c5b05ebf33aba364d2999c47e18'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Existing, under construction and planned low to mid-rise apartments identified](index_files/figure-html/fig-nodes-corridors-planned-1.png){#fig-nodes-corridors-planned-1 width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Existing, under construction and planned low to mid-rise apartments removed](index_files/figure-html/fig-nodes-corridors-planned-2.png){#fig-nodes-corridors-planned-2 width=672}
:::

Nodes and corridors around McKernan/Belgravia station
:::


I've stitched all of this together in an animation below in @fig-nodes-corridors-animated, to show the progression as we remove more and more sites that probably won't see higher density than today under the proposed district plan. Remember that BC's new legislation applied to McKernan/Belgravia Station would support 8 storeys over 100% of the station area (minus parks, fire halls, etc) and even taller buildings within the 400m and 200m radii. So even the generous 31% node and corridor area coverage using the raw data is conservative in comparison.


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/fig-nodes-corridors-animated_71a20c33d8fd6187d4f4db20b177acf1'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Progression of node and corridor coverage around McKernan/Belgravia Station](index_files/figure-html/fig-nodes-corridors-animated-1.gif){#fig-nodes-corridors-animated}
:::
:::


## Conclusion and how to move forward

The Scona district plan is certainly an improvement on the area redevelopment plan, allowing higher densities along 76 Ave and 114 St. However, we need to fully leverage every one of the few rapid transit stations in Edmonton to avoid a spreading Canadian housing crisis, dial back sprawl and achieve the city's target of 50% infill development. This especially applies to the least used station on the LRT network, one that is also a short walk away from the University of Alberta.

BC's government has set a new bar in Canada for transit-oriented development and that's where we should start. There is no good reason why a random spot between the twin four-lane stroads of Calgary Trail and Gateway should be designated for high density, but a site that's a five minute walk from McKernan/Belgravia Station should only be designated for low density.

![Scona district map, cropped](mckernan_belgravia_station_district_map.png){#fig-scona-district-map}

Higher density permissions around major transit stations should be written into the district plans. It shouldn't matter whether rapid transit stations are within a primary corridor, secondary corridor, major node or none of them. This can happen before the final draft district policy and plans are brought back to council in 2024 or in subsequent amendments by council. If you agree with me, please a few minutes to tell City Planning this in their [district policy survey](https://cityofedmonton.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_cOtuG43o6YNnAea?EE) and as always, sign up for the [Grow Together Edmonton](https://www.gtyeg.ca/) mailing list to stay up-to-date on Edmonton housing news.

*Are there any other LRT stations I should do?* *Did I get anything wrong? Let me know in the comments.*
